    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1928-10-19T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1928-10-19T00:00:00-05:00" n="254"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d254">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.744/20</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Bulgaria</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Kodding</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Sofia</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1928-10-19">October 19,
                            1928</date>.<lb/>[Received November 10.]</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 1337</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to request instructions
                    concerning the procedure to be followed in the application of the Naturalization
                    Treaty between the United States and Bulgaria proclaimed on May 6, 1924.<note
                        n="7" xml:id="d254fn7">Signed November 23, 1923; see <ref
                            target="frus1923v01#pg_464">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1923, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, p. 464</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>It may be noted that in the Department’s Instruction No. 165 of March 25,
                        1926,<note n="8" xml:id="d254fn8">Not printed.</note> it was desired that a
                    Bulgarian emigrant to the United States who subsequently became a naturalized
                    American citizen be relieved of the necessity of paying Bulgarian taxes from the
                    date of his emigration to the United States. In the Department’s Instruction No.
                    176 of July 13, 1926<note n="8" xml:id="d254fn9">Not printed.</note> it was
                    desired, however, that the Bulgarian Government remit only such taxes as had
                    been collected from an emigrant subsequent to the date of his naturalization as
                    an American citizen.</p>
                <p>It may be stated that in no single case has the Bulgarian Government been willing
                    to release its former subjects from taxation from any date previous to their
                    naturalization as American citizens.</p>
                <p>A case involving the above interpretations of the Bulgarian-American
                    Naturalization Treaty is now pending and I respectfully recommend that the
                    Legation be authorized to adopt the latter policy providing no legal objection
                    is perceived to it.</p>
                <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">T. Kodding</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
